answers.body_markdown:
You answers:

1. I don&#39;t think that there are better way that just direct measurement of how long `exec` runs.

2. Profiler is the only way (`valgrind`). However, profiler will influence performance (it will decrease it drammatically). While process is still running, you can check its memory usage via following command:

    `grep VmPeak /proc/$PID/status`

Precision will be very bad, and for quick process similar to `echo` you can even have no time to run this shell command. 

3. Check exit codes (from `g++` and `./code`) to check for errors. It is guaranteed for `g++`, about custom program, it may have custom logic and use its own protocol to report error, but generally if the `./code` follows common practice, it must set exit code to nonzero on error.

However, generally speaking, there are not guaranteed way to understand whether the program runs correctly, because &quot;correctly&quot; is about semantics and not about pure coding. &quot;Correctly&quot; is how the software author wants it to work. If software author thinks that the software must exit with specific code, he can do it independently from any internal errors.

See this code for example:

    #include &lt;iostream&gt;
    #include &lt;cstdlib&gt;
    
    int main()
    {
        int z = 1;
        int y = 1;
        int x = 1 / (z - y);
        return 0;
    }

It generates &quot;division by zero&quot; exception.

Lets compile and execute it:

    $ g++ program_1.cpp -o program_1
    $ ./program_1
    Floating point exception (core dumped)
    $ echo $?
    136

The program exits with code `136`; the reason is that default division by zero signal handler implemented by C runtime exits with this code.

If we add our own signal handler, the exit code will still be `0`:

    #include &lt;iostream&gt;
    #include &lt;cstdlib&gt;
    
    #include &lt;sys/types.h&gt;
    #include &lt;signal.h&gt;
    
    void signal_handler (int signo) 
    {
        if(signo == SIGFPE) 
            exit(0);
    }
    
    int main()
    {
        signal(SIGFPE,(*signal_handler));
        int z = 1;
        int y = 1;
        int x = 1 / (z - y);
        return 0;
    }

So, when you run completely unknown external code, it is near impossible to understand what does it really do; it is how viruses work for example, they behave in different way than you expect.

